name: Carrabeanga
description:
Note Feb 2023: These notes have not been updated post the fires and exceptional regrowth. The following is from 2019.

Carrabeanga is one of the hardest, if not the hardest, of the canyons flowing into Kanangra Creek. It is a remote wilderness trip requiring advanced navigational and ropework skills. All of the party should have previous experience in Kanangra canyons. Travel light and fast.

Carrabeanga is not recommended as a winter trip, despite what you may see elsewhere.

Carrabeanga is not a one-day car-to-car trip.

It is sensible to drop water on the way in for the return trip.

Approach

See also the GPX from Thurat_Rift, which as at summer 23/24 is more accurate on the approach (until the ways diverge).

Allow 2h30m for the walk in.

Park at the King Pin Firetrail on the Kanangra Walls road. Follow the King Pin Firetrail to Mount Thurat. Follow the ridge along Thurat Tops (difficult routefinding, use Thurat_Rift GPX) to the intersection of Thurat Ridge and Burra Gunama Ridge at -33.94090,150.10526. Drop water here for the return trip. Follow Burra Gunama Ridge to Burra Gunama Hill. Walk down to Carrabeanga Brook, aiming to strike the river at -33.93429, 150.13121. Walk downstream to the first anchor at -33.93467, 150.13218.

Descent

Follow the attached abseil summary list, and diagram of the Carrabeanga Falls. Pay particular attention to the comments for abseils 5, 6 and 7.

Exit

After an overnight camp on Kanangra Creek, exit via the ridge to the south of Cyclops Gully.
